2. Word Frequency

  1. Convert the description to tokens, remove all the stop words. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 20th century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words.
# Converting the description to tokens and removing all stop words. The data is then sorted by word frequency, filtered by the 20th century, and the first 10 rows are displayed. The dataframe is turned into a bar plot.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(century == 20) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col(fill = 'seagreen2', color = 'black') +
  labs(y = 'Word', x = 'Frequency')

  1. What are the top 10 frequent words of movies/TV Shows in the 21st century. Plot the bar chart of the frequency of these words. Plot a side-by-side bar charts to compare the most frequent words by the two centuries.
# This plot was made in the same manner as the previous one, but the data is instead filtered by the 21st century.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  filter(century == 21) %>% 
  head(10) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = n, y = reorder(word, n))) +
  geom_col(fill = 'palevioletred2', color = 'black') +
  labs(y = 'Word', x = 'Frequency')

# A plot is made using the 'facet_wrap()' function to compare the description words between the two centuries.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(century) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = century)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = century)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~century, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Frequency",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()

4. Sentiment Analysis

  1. Is movies/TV Shows in the 21st century tends to be more positive than those in 20th century? Use the sentiment analysis by Bing lexicons to address the question.
# Analyzing sentiment with 'Bing' and plotting the results for both centuries. From the plot below, it is clear that movies / tv shows from the 20th century tend to be more positive than the movies from the 21st century.

df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

  1. Do sentiment analysis using nrc and afinn lexicons. Give your comments on the results.
# Importing the 'textdata' library
library(textdata)

# This time, a sentiment analysis is performed with the 'nrc' lexicon. Words such as surprise, negative, and disgust were used more in the 21st century. The other words are used at roughly the same frequency.
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("nrc")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(sentiment, n, fill=century))+geom_col(position = 'fill')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

## ℹ Row 8 of `x` matches multiple rows in `y`.
## ℹ Row 7729 of `y` matches multiple rows in `x`.
## ℹ If a many-to-many relationship is expected, set `relationship =

# Using 'afinn' for sentiment analysis. There has not been much change in the sentiments used between the two centuries. However, there appears to be less extreme words used in the 21st century with more words in the middle of the range (-5,5) meaning that the graph has become more condensed. 
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = description, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(century, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(century) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("afinn")) %>%
    mutate(sentiment = value) %>% 
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(century) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(century, n, fill=factor(sentiment)))+geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', fill = 'Sentiment', x = '')

5. Modeling

  1. Use the description to predict if a movie/TV show is in 20th or 21st century. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table.
# Importing libraries for text mining.
library(caret)
library(themis)
library(textrecipes)

# Select data and set target 
df1 <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = century) %>% 
  select(target, description) 

# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~description,
       data = df1) %>% 
  step_tokenize(description) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(description, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(description) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df1 <- juice(a)

# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(42)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df1$target, p = .7, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df1[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df1[-splitIndex,]

forest_ranger <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "ranger")

pred <- predict(forest_ranger, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.9811449
# Plotting the confusion matrix table
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
library(yardstick)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot

  1. Create variable century2 taking three following values. (Hint: You can use the case_when function to do this)
- `21` if released_year is greater or equal to 2000

- `second_half_20`if released_year is greater than or equal to 1950 and less than 2000

- `first_half_20` otherwise

Predict century2 using the descriptions. Give the accuracy and plot the confusion matrix table. (Notice that the codes for 8 should still work for this question)

# Creating and adding the `century2` variable to the dataframe with case_when.
df$century2 <- case_when(
  df$release_year <1950  ~ 'first_half_20',
  df$release_year <=1999 ~ 'second_half_20',
  TRUE ~ '21'
)

# A plot is made using the 'facet_wrap()' function to compare the description words between the two rating cetegories.
df %>%
  unnest_tokens(input = text, output = word) %>% 
  anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
  count(rating, word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  group_by(rating) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 10) %>% 
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(word = reorder_within(word, by = n, within = rating)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, word, fill = rating)) +
  geom_col(show.legend = FALSE) +
  facet_wrap(~rating, scales = "free") +
  labs(x = "Frequency",
       y = NULL)+
  scale_y_reordered()

# Analyzing sentiment with 'Bing' and plotting the results for both rating categories. As expected, the 'bad' category of ratings had more negative words used than the 'good' rating category. Surprisingly the 'good' rating category had more negative words than positive words. 
df %>%
    unnest_tokens(input = text, output = word) %>% 
    anti_join(get_stopwords()) %>% 
    count(rating, word, sort = TRUE) %>%
    group_by(rating) %>% 
    inner_join(get_sentiments("bing")) %>%
    filter(!is.na(sentiment)) %>%
    count(sentiment, sort = TRUE) %>% 
    group_by(rating) %>% 
    mutate(n = n/sum(n)) %>% 
    ggplot(aes(rating, n, fill=sentiment))+geom_col(position = 'dodge')+
    labs(y='Relative Frequency', x ='')

# Training a flexible discriminant analysis model. The accuracy has been evaluated at ~0.7956.

# Select data and set target 
df1 <- df %>% 
  mutate(target = rating) %>% 
  select(target, text) 

# Convert text data to numeric variables
a <- recipe(target~text,
       data = df1) %>% 
  step_tokenize(text) %>% 
  step_tokenfilter(text, max_tokens = 50) %>% 
  step_tfidf(text) %>% 
  step_normalize(all_numeric_predictors()) %>% 
  step_smote(target) %>% 
  prep()
df1 <- juice(a)

# Using Caret for modeling
set.seed(42)
splitIndex <- createDataPartition(df1$target, p = .7, 
                                  list = FALSE)
df_train <- df1[ splitIndex,]
df_test <- df1[-splitIndex,]

fda <- train(target~., data=df_train, 
                        method = "fda")

pred <- predict(fda, df_test)

cm <- confusionMatrix(data = pred, reference = df_test$target)
cm$overall[1]
##  Accuracy 
## 0.7947368
# Plotting the confusion matrix table
d = data.frame(pred = pred, obs = df_test$target)
d %>% conf_mat(pred, obs) %>% autoplot
